<article>
    <h1>South China Sea &#x2022; Trump or Bi&#xAD;den, In&#xAD;done&#xAD;sia will main&#xAD;tain neu&#xAD;tral&#xAD;ity in South China Sea</h1>
    <h2>By adopt&#xAD;ing a prag&#xAD;matic ap&#xAD;proach in at&#xAD;tract&#xAD;ing for&#xAD;eign in&#xAD;vest&#xAD;ments to boost its do&#xAD;mes&#xAD;tic econ&#xAD;omy, Jakarta avoids get&#xAD;ting dragged into the US-China ri&#xAD;valry, say ex&#xAD;perts</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201106/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-06"><time>2020-11-06</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ar&#xAD;lina Ar&#xAD;shad Re&#xAD;gional Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent&#xD;&#xA;ar&#xAD;lina@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Whether Mr Don­ald Trump or Mr Joe Bi­den be­comes the next pres­i­dent of the United States, In­done­sia will main­tain its neu­tral­ity in the South China Sea amid sim­mer­ing ten­sions be­tween US and China, an­a­lysts say.</p>
    <p>When US Sec­re­tary of State</p>
    <p>Mike Pom­peo vis­ited Jakarta on Oct 28, just a week be­fore the US elec­tion, he ex­pressed Washington’s readi­ness to co­op­er­ate “in new ways” to en­sure mar­itime se­cu­rity and pro­tect other busy trade routes from uni­lat­eral claims by China.</p>
    <p>In­done­sia’s For­eign Min­is­ter Retno Mar­sudi, how­ever, called on US busi­nesses to in­vest in the Natuna Is­lands in the South China Sea, which has been at the cen­tre of diplo­matic ten­sions with China over mar­itime rights.</p>
    <p>The move has been hailed by an­a­lysts as a “smart ap­proach” by Pres­i­dent Joko Wi­dodo’s ad­min­is­tra­tion to safe­guard In­done­sia’s sovereignt­y over the chain of is­lands off the coast of Bor­neo, with­out get­ting dragged into the ri­valry be­tween the two global pow­ers.</p>
    <p>An­a­lysts say US and China ten­sions are not likely to die down re­gard­less of who is the next US pres­i­dent. “Bi­den and Trump are politi­cians who come and go. The bu­reau­cracy is the one in charge of poli­cies,” in­ter­na­tional law ex­pert Hikma­hanto Juwana told</p>
    <p>The Straits Times.</p>
    <p>He added that Jakarta’s Natu­nas of­fer to for­eign in­vestors is to pro­tect the coun­try’s na­tional in­ter­est, es­pe­cially since</p>
    <p>In­done­sia has not been able to ad­e­quately ex­ploit its re­sources and su­per­vise its wa­ters.</p>
    <p>“More im­por­tantly, In­done­sia is driv­ing home a point that it is not mak­ing claims based on a map alone,” he said.</p>
    <p>The US is among In­done­sia’s top mil­i­tary part­ners, while China is its sec­ond-big­gest source of for­eign di­rect in­vest­ment, af­ter Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>“Tac­ti­cally, we will def­i­nitely get in­vest­ments... to strengthen the econ­omy in In­done­sia’s fron­tier re­gions,” mil­i­tary and de­fence an­a­lyst Con­nie Ra­hakun­dini Bakrie told ST.</p>
    <p>“And strate­gi­cally, this is a smart way in which In­done­sia brings in US pres­ence with­out hav­ing to es­ca­late it to the mil­i­tary level, hence avoid­ing a hos­tile en­vi­ron­ment for all par­ties.”</p>
    <p>A se­ries of tres­passes by</p>
    <p>Chi­nese fish­ing boats, es­corted by the coun­try’s coast guard ves­sels, in the Natu­nas prompted Jakarta to beef up se­cu­rity and sur­veil­lance and even name the area North Natuna Sea.</p>
    <p>While Bei­jing has not claimed con­trol over the is­lands, it does claim the right to fish in the sur­round­ing wa­ters which it says over­lap with its self-pro­claimed “nine-dash line” in the South</p>
    <p>China Sea.</p>
    <p>Jakarta has strongly op­posed this, as­sert­ing that In­done­sia’s ex­clu­sive eco­nomic zone ex­tends 200 nau­ti­cal miles from shore.</p>
    <p>The area is rich in marine life and fish species, as well as crude oil and nat­u­ral gas re­serves.</p>
    <p>Be­sides state-owned oil and gas com­pany Per­tam­ina, other com­pa­nies op­er­at­ing there in­clude Hous­ton-based Cono­coPhillips and</p>
    <p>Sin­ga­pore-based Star En­ergy.</p>
    <p>The In­done­sian gov­ern­ment has ex­tended a sim­i­lar of­fer to other coun­tries, in­clud­ing Ja­pan.</p>
    <p>When Ja­panese For­eign Min­is­ter Toshim­itsu Motegi vis­ited Jakarta in Jan­uary, fol­low­ing an­other stand-off with China in Natuna, Pres­i­dent Joko also urged Ja­panese busi­nesses to in­crease in­vest­ments in fish­ery and en­ergy there.</p>
    <p>Whether it is the US, China or any other coun­try, In­done­sia is sim­ply adopt­ing a prag­matic ap­proach in at­tract­ing for­eign in­vest­ments to boost its do­mes­tic econ­omy, In­done­sian In­sti­tute of Sciences re­searcher Adri­ana Elis­a­beth said.</p>
    <p>“In­done­sia is like a swing state, get­ting pulled by the US and China on ei­ther side,” she told ST.</p>
    <p>“In­done­sia must be more ag­ile in seiz­ing the op­por­tu­ni­ties but main­tain the stance that it will not be in­flu­enced by US or Chi­nese in­ter­ests.”</p>

